propOverview: 2070 S 7th Street is an opportunity to sublease a critical warehouse and shipping space in the heart of San Jose. The available suite has around 9,700 square feet of built-out offices with open areas and private offices, including a conference room with a table and chairs. The remainder consists of a large 84,000 square-foot processing warehouse and a 26,500 square-foot shipping warehouse. The warehouses feature 22’ clear height, heavy power, and a large mezzanine for storage. The shipping warehouse has four, front-loading interior docks, as well as a sloped driveway to a drive-in door connecting the building to its paved and fenced lot outside. There is also a loading dock at the rear of the processing warehouse. 2070 S 7th Street has excellent access to some of the region’s major transportation and distribution channels. From the building, it is only 5 minutes to either Guadalupe Freeway or I-280, opening up access to Silicon Valley and the entire Bay Area. Multimodal shipping options are readily available as well with San Jose Distribution Services adjacent to the building and the Port of Redwood City reachable in a 37-minute drive. The San Jose metropolitan area offers an excellent and skilled labor force. Over 1.4-million people are residing in a 10-mile radius, and manufacturing, transportation, and warehousing make up 18.5% of all jobs in the metro.

extraInfo: Rental Rate,$4.00 /SF/YR,Property Subtype,Manufacturing,Total Space Available,153,834 SF,Rentable Building Area,153,835 SF,Max. Contiguous,76,917 SF,Year Built,1900,Property Type,Industrial
highlights: Located between Rockett's Landing and Shockoe Bottom in the City of Richmond, Virginia.
propOverview:
The Armitage Building is a two-story warehouse building located between Rockett's Landing and Shockoe Bottom in the City of Richmond, Virginia. The two-story Armitage Building is a warehouse complex that stands on the north side of Williamsburg Avenue on an approx. 4.56 acre parcel in the City of Richmond with Libby Hill Park to the west and Stone Brewing to the east.
The property was originally the headquarters of the Armitage Manufacturing Company, which produced tar paper roofing materials. The main portion of the building was built in 1900. It was designed by the Richmond firm Noland & Baskervill, now known as Baskervill, when the firm was just three years old.
The industrial building consists primarily of two wings, with the original two-story brick-constructed plant built in 1900 for the production of building supplies and roofing paper, and then used for corrugated container manufacturing. In 1954, a large barrel-roofed, metal bowstring truss wing was added to the rear corner of the warehouse.

highlights: Scott's Addition Location,Conditioned Interior,Flexible TOD-1 Zoning Permits Many Commercial Uses
propOverview:
FLEXIBLE COMMERCIAL SPACE IN SCOTT'S ADDITION
One South Commercial is pleased to present for lease this flexible commercial space in the heart of dynamic Scott’s Addition. The 8,400 SF space is currently set up as a printing/warehouse facility and features roll-up doors, high-ceiling, open plan, and a fully conditioned interior. The area available for lease can be demised or increased, please contact agent for details.
In addition to its current use, the TOD-1 Transit Oriented zoning allows for a number of commercial uses including office, retail, and restaurant. Accordingly, the space could potentially be adapted as a creative workspace, lifestyle center, or Scott’s Addition’s latest trend-setting eatery.
Redevelopment in Scott’s Addition in recent years has transformed this formerly industrial area into one of the most exciting mixed-use neighborhoods in Richmond with  distinctive adaptively repurposed multifamily  apartments,  food and entertainment establishments, and  popular commercial uses. Combined with great accessibility from GRTC’s Pulse Rapid Transit on Broad Street, 1511 Altamont Ave is the perfect location for a business looking to locate in Scott’s Addition.
Note: Lease rate is $8-15/SF/NNN, contact agent for details.

spaceSummary:
Diamond Hill Distribution Center is an institutional grade three building industrial complex that comprises of over 700,000 Sq. Ft. of high-bay warehouse/distribution space. The 1960 Diamond Hill Road building is 267,000 Sq. Ft. with multiple dock and grade level loading doors as well as numerous rail loading doors with access to Norfolk Southern via a private (currently inactive) rail spur. The property also affords tenants with a secure outside storage yard. ESFR sprinkler system and T5 lighting available. The property is Institutionally owned by Link Industrial Properties.

Link Industrial Properties is Blackstone’s US industrial real estate operating platform. Link currently manages a national portfolio of high-quality, well-located industrial assets totaling over 355 million square feet throughout the U.S.

The property is centrally located in the heart of the Hampton Roads region. It's location inside the "beltway loop", provides immediate access to all of the freight terminals that make up the Port of Virginia; which benefits tenants with some of the lowest drayage rates in the region. The property has immediate access to the major arterial highways in the region (I-64, I-464, and I-264) as well as the thriving Greenbrier area of Chesapeake, which affords tenants with numerous time-saving retail, banking, and restaurant establishments.

spaceSummary:
650 S. Rock Blvd. Building #14 is an excellent, environmentally friendly space for an owner/user. Previously occupied by architectural and engineering firms, the building features open naturally lighted office areas, all with views of the Sierras. The building’s power is augmented with an architecturally unique awning of solar panels that also provide significant shading; all resulting in very, very low energy cost. 
The two-story building has three units with separate entrances. The lower level is separated into two office spaces that are approximately 750/sf each. These units share a common break area, kitchen and bathroom. These two units can easily be combined for a single user.
The second floor is 1,368 square feet of open office space with a private restroom. The west facing wall is exposed brick. Large windows and multiple solar tubes provide natural light and a healthy, productive working environment. There are also multiple workout gyms, and a Yoga Studio in the complex.
The building is located directly across from Atlantic Air; the Fixed Based Operator (private airport) for the Reno/Tahoe Airport. It is centrally located with an average of 14,000 cars passing each day. Its easy accessed location is only minutes from downtown Reno or Sparks, as well as both 1-80 and 1-580 the main arterials of Reno/Sparks.
****Please Call to Schedule a Video Tour Today!****,650 S. Rock Blvd #18 consists of approximately 2,396 square feet of rentable space. The property is single story. There are restroom facilities onsite one with a shower. The property is zoned MUDR which allows for a wide range of users. The building is primarily located. It fronts Rock Blvd across the street from the private airport terminal at Reno Airport. The traffic count for S. Rock is over 13,000 cars per day. This is an excellent opportunity for an investor or owner user.

propOverview:
Property Website: www.cbre.us/centergateatgratigny
Centergate @ Gratigny I & II is a 1,580,821 SF Class A industrial property featuring two newly constructed state-of-the-art distribution buildings totaling 602,657 SF (Centergate II), as well as a 978,164 SF distribution and light assembly warehouse (Centergate I).
Built in 1999, Centergate I features cross-dock and side loading with ample doors, 110’-170’ deep truck courts and abundant auto parking, with 1.31 spaces per 1,000 SF. Centergate II, built in 2016, features 32’ clear span height 233’ deep rear load buildings with 185’ deep truck courts, 2.6 doors per 10,000 SF and 1.1 spaces per 1,000 SF.
With frontage on and great visibility from the Gratigny Expressway (SR 924), in the heartland of Miami’s Hialeah submarket, Centergate features excellent access to key South Florida regional logistical infrastructure. With immediate access to the Gratigny Expressway, all of Miami’s major roadways are easily accessible, with I-95 and I-75/Palmetto Expressway (SR 826) interchange only 3.0 and 4.0 miles away, respectively, from the Gratigny on ramps.

propOverview:
Stream Data Centers’ newly constructed DFW VII facility is an expandable 138,132 square foot data center with a new on-site Oncor substation and dual (2) dedicated underground 40 MW utility feeds, predesigned to support full capacity of the campus.
Ultimately, in future phases, the campus will total approximately 400,000 square feet of data center space. Today Stream’s DFW VII data center features:
A 22.66-acre site in Garland, Texas located on Lookout Drive, in close proximity to robust Northeast Dallas, Richardson and Garland amenities, power and fiber infrastructure.
Initial 138,132 square-foot structurally enhanced facility with land available for multiple phases, and 75,000 square feet of fully commissioned data hall space.
Two (2) 40 MW utility feeds from a new on-site Oncor substation offering power at competitive transmission rates, and options for renewable energy.
Two (2) diverse telco entrances, with multiple fiber providers and a strong mix of local, long haul and dark fiber providers to the site through multiple routes.
Designed to meet or exceed size and capital investment requirements under House Bill 1223 sales tax exemption program.
Optimal location outside of flight paths, railways and FEMA 500-year flood plain.
Multiple network service providers are engaged for diverse dark fiber paths back to the major carrier hotels and cloud interconnection locations, allowing our customers to expand beyond the providers that are in the immediate area with access to 100+ network and cloud providers.
Three MW of existing critical load with expansion growth to thirty MW.

hoodMarket: The Northeast Dallas area is a well-established, in-town industrial center in the metroplex. The area is diverse and can be segmented by areas inside LBJ Freeway and outside LBJ Freeway. The largest concentration of industrial tenants fall outside of LBJ Freeway towards Garland. An outer ring suburb, Garland is one of Dallas-Fort Worth’s original boomburbs, with heavy concentrations of industrial employment and blue-collar employment base. ,Geography and transportation are strategic considerations for tenants in this part of Dallas. The area includes primary transportation arteries: the LBJ Freeway, U.S. 75 North, and in the outer section, President George Bush Tollway. The existing tenant base includes manufacturing firms, retail and wholesalers, and transportation. The largest tenants include Kraft Foods, which has a large manufacturing location in Garland; home goods store At Home, which has a large distribution facility; and watch retailer Fossil, which has space near its corporate headquarters in Richardson.,With one of the largest existing inventories of industrial buildings, new construction in Northeast Dallas has been limited compared to other rapidly growing areas of Dallas-Fort Worth. Largely built-out, available land is the biggest constraint for new buildings.,Given excellent highway and rail access, robust leasing activity is keeping vacancies low. Rental rates are on par with the Dallas-Fort Worth average.

1,500 and 1,800 sf Flex-Space Warehouse with private office and restroom, with direct exposure to/and from I-75 in an exclusive gated and secure commerce park with great parking.
CBS Construction with Pre-Cast reinforced Twin-T concrete roof deck 19 feet Clear heights which can accommodate greater storage, and large overhead 02doors
Easy Access;
Just off ramp I-75 & 138th St. between the city of Hialeah, with one of the largest labor markets in Dade County and the prestigious Miami Lakes with first class hotels, restaurants, residential areas, golf clubs, shopping centers, banks and medical & office complexes.
Located in One of Dade County’s Most Desirable Areas
Sitting in the heart of northwest Dade and with convenient access from the entire tri-county area, via (I-75), Palmetto Expy.(SR826), Gratigny Expy.(916)(924), Florida Turnpike(821), W Okeechobee Rd.(27)(25), Dolphin Expy.(836) and (I-95) Direct access to Opa-Locka Executive Airport and close proximity to Miami International Airport and the Port of Miami.
First Class Customer Service and flexibility
As owner-operator of our portfolio of Warehouses we can offer you total flexibility so you can, downsize, upsize or relocate and first-class customer service at our Buildings is guaranteed since all our tenants deal directly with our in-house experienced team of professionals - not a third-party management company representative with limited decision-making authority.
* Square footage and/or dimensions are approximations and may vary between individual units

hoodMarket: South Pinellas is the largest industrial market in the Tampa region, benefitting from the St. Pete-Clearwater International Airport and direct access to Interstate 275, which connects to Florida’s two primary arterial roadways, Interstates 4 and 75. South Pinellas is located within a same-day round-trip drive to all Florida markets. Industrial construction has been limited over the past decade, and as a result, the industrial inventory here is a bit older than the Tampa market average.,South Pinellas has benefitted from both traditional industrial demand as well as tenants’ more modern needs. Historically, the tenant mix in South Pinellas has been dominated by the aerospace and defense industries, but the rise of e-commerce has fueled industrial demand in warehouses targeting last-mile deliveries servicing the local population. Competition in this niche sector is becoming fierce, with the older inventory and relatively lower ceiling heights limiting the total available space for prospective tenants. The South Pinellas industrial market is now incredibly tight, with average occupancy rates near the highest on record.,Asking rents here vary widely across property types and due to South Pinellas’ large geography. However, industrial average rents are in general above the Tampa market average. Perhaps the market’s biggest draw for industrial tenants is the established inventory and industrial infrastructure, allowing most spaces to immediately fit a variety of needs.

propOverview:
This Southwest industrial building is zoned I-2 / General Industrial and is well suited for manufacturing or warehouse operations. There is 973 SF of office on the first floor and 1,006 SF on the second floor, for a total of 1,979 SF. There is 31,630 SF of manufacturing/warehouse. This building comes with (1) 12’x12’ OH door, (1) 8’x8’ OH door, (4) 8’x12’ dock doors and (1) 8’x9’ dock door. The building is equipped with 480 volt / 400 amp / 3 phase power. It is situated in a small industrial park with neighbors like PPG Coating Services, LH Carbide, All Season Storage, Only Alpha Pool Products, Vision Lighting Corp, Park Plastic Products and System Science Institute. The surrounding area is comprised of mostly industrial and service business but is close to restaurants and retail shopping.

propOverview:
Historic features give the building unique character. Constructed in 1905 for use as a creamery, The Dairy House is one of Lincoln' s most significant historic resources and delivers a one-of-kind space for office, retail, restaurant, storage and light industrial. High ceilings, large windows, exposed brick walls and wood timbers produce an ideal shell for custom creative or traditional tenant improvements. All buildings utilize geothermal HVAC systems and solar energy to optimize both performance and cost efficiency. 
Located in the South Haymarket, the Dairy House is surrounded by shops, bars, restaurants, student housing, offices and hotels. Close to UNL campus, Pinnacle Bank Arena, the State Capital and County/City offices. This prime, high-traffic location offers a coveted opportunity to be in the heart of Lincoln's premier Entertainment and Business District.
The Diary House complex fills the entire block of L Street from South 7th Street to South 8th Street and North to M Street.
This raw shell is full of potential, build-to-suit your needs.

highlights: Ideally located in The Black Mountain Master Planned Industrial Park and surrounded by the Henderson Auto Center and dense residential areas.,Environmentally conscious building with clean tenant uses, there are solar panels installed providing power to a portion of the building.,The building has easy access to the entire valley, only 2 minutes to either I-215 or I-515 and 12 minutes to McCarran International Airport.,Excellent demographics with 104,000 people in a 3-mile radius and over 24,000 cars passing each day on N Gibson Road.
hoodMarket: The Henderson industrial area in southeast Las Vegas covers the city of Henderson and the nearby neighborhoods of Green Valley, Silverado Ranch, Seven Hills, and Macdonald Ranch. The Interstate 215 and Interstate 515, along with the Union Pacific Railroad, run along the southern portion of the area providing several transportation corridors for Henderson’s logistics, manufacturing and warehousing tenants. Henderson is located about 10 miles from McCarran International Airport, a major transportation hub for the region. The Henderson area is home to a mix of business and residential uses, along with Henderson Executive Airport and the Raider’s office space and training center. ,Industrial properties in the Henderson area are primarily clustered near the intersection of the Interstate 215 and Interstate 515 freeways, in close proximity to residential nodes. Both employers and residents can take advantage of the numerous restaurants and retailers that are scattered across the area. These are among the reasons Henderson has become home to a number of master-planned industrial parks with companies including Smith’s Food & Drug, FedEx Ground, Levi Strauss & Co, and Google occupying significant footprints in the area.,New development in the Henderson area has been moderate this cycle and vacancies are tight and well below the region’s average. Average rent levels in the area are at a discount to the region’s average, offering a more affordable option close to freeways and population nodes.

hoodMarket: Moreno Valley and Perris are among the fastest growing industrial neighborhoods in the Inland Empire. One of the few areas where relatively affordable land is still available, Infrastructure is well built out, and the very-limited residential housing nearby it amenable to industrial uses. ,The neighborhood is valued for its connectivity. Multiple freeways provide access to the twin ports of Los Angeles and Long Beach, as well as to points north and east. These transportation corridors also allow easy access to the abundant labor pool in nearby Riverside and south Riverside County, where ample housing remains affordable.,Strong demand for big box distribution space has matched the pace of construction. Amazon leases four distribution buildings here with between 800,000 and 1.25 million square feet. Other major occupants include Lowe’s, Sketchers, UPS, Whirlpool, Ross, General Mills, and Proctor & Gamble. Despite high rent growth over the past five years, the average rent in the area is still about 40% lower than rents in Los Angeles or Orange County.

propOverview: LogistiCenter at Park Meridian, located at 21822 Opportunity Way, is situated on a 13.53-acre site within the master-planned Meridian Business Center in Riverside, California. This 262,260 square-foot freestanding facility delivered in 2019 and comes equipped with all of the features necessary for today’s industrial businesses. Features include 2,943 square feet of dedicated office space that can be customized, a cross-docking layout with 56 9’x10’ loading docks and two 12’x15’ ground level doors, and a 135’ and a 185’ secured truck court with 45 trailer parking stalls. Additionally, the building offers 50’x52’ column spacing, a 32’ clear height, and a 2,000-amp main switchboard with a 4,000-amp pull section. LogistiCenter at Park Meridian benefits from its location within Foreign Trade Zone No. 244 and immediate access to I-215 via the recently re-engineered and expanded Van Buren Boulevard interchange and the nearby Cactus Avenue and Alessandro Boulevard interchanges. The property also sits just three miles south of the I-215/SR-60 interchange and the I-215 South Corridor, which is home to a prestigious list of corporate occupiers including Amazon, Nissan, UPS, Sysco Corporation, KIA Motors, Burlington, McLane Foods, Lowe’s and Home Depot.
